</span><span><span></span><span class="token token title" style="color: rgb(43, 48, 59); font-weight: bold;">##</span><span class="token token title" style="color: rgb(184, 10, 24); font-weight: bold;"> Executive Summary</span><span>
</span></span><span>
</span><span>The Open Knowledge Work Foundation (OKWF) proposes to build 
</span><span>infrastructure that enables qualified individuals outside 
</span><span>traditional employment markets to make meaningful, compensated 
</span><span>contributions to knowledge-intensive projects through 
</span><span>AI-coordinated specialization.
</span><span>
</span><span>We identify a systemic market failure: frontier AI companies 
</span><span>have hundreds of unfilled senior positions (Anthropic alone had 
</span><span>440 open roles as of April 2026), while simultaneously, 
</span><span>substantial talent pools remain underutilized due to geographic, 
</span><span>regulatory, health, or life-stage constraints. This includes 
</span><span>retired experts, disabled specialists, career-switchers, and 
</span><span>domain experts in non-CS backgrounds. Existing staffing platforms 
</span><span>(Deel, Toptal, Upwork, Mercor) treat these populations as 
</span><span>transactional labor, not as dignified contributors with persistent 
</span><span>professional identity.
</span><span>
</span><span>OKWF proposes a foundation-funded infrastructure combining:
</span><span>
</span><span><span></span><span class="token token list" style="color: rgb(43, 48, 59);">1.</span><span> </span><span class="token token bold" style="color: rgb(43, 48, 59);">**</span><span class="token token bold content">Nautilus Portal Protocol</span><span class="token token bold" style="color: rgb(43, 48, 59);">**</span><span> — open technical substrate for 
</span></span><span>   federated knowledge work
</span><span><span></span><span class="token token list" style="color: rgb(43, 48, 59);">2.</span><span> </span><span class="token token bold" style="color: rgb(43, 48, 59);">**</span><span class="token token bold content">Double-Triangle Architecture</span><span class="token token bold" style="color: rgb(43, 48, 59);">**</span><span> — human-AI collaboration 
</span></span><span>   pattern preserving individual autonomy
</span><span><span></span><span class="token token list" style="color: rgb(43, 48, 59);">3.</span><span> </span><span class="token token bold" style="color: rgb(43, 48, 59);">**</span><span class="token token bold content">Pattern library with private instances</span><span class="token token bold" style="color: rgb(43, 48, 59);">**</span><span> — compounding 
</span></span><span>   shared knowledge without privacy loss
</span><span><span></span><span class="token token list" style="color: rgb(43, 48, 59);">4.</span><span> </span><span class="token token bold" style="color: rgb(43, 48, 59);">**</span><span class="token token bold content">Guild-based community structure</span><span class="token token bold" style="color: rgb(43, 48, 59);">**</span><span> — persistent professional 
</span></span><span>   identity across engagements
</span><span><span></span><span class="token token list" style="color: rgb(43, 48, 59);">5.</span><span> </span><span class="token token bold" style="color: rgb(43, 48, 59);">**</span><span class="token token bold content">Graduated participation model</span><span class="token token bold" style="color: rgb(43, 48, 59);">**</span><span> — entry at any capacity, 
</span></span><span>   progression at individual pace
</span><span><span></span><span class="token token list" style="color: rgb(43, 48, 59);">6.</span><span> </span><span class="token token bold" style="color: rgb(43, 48, 59);">**</span><span class="token token bold content">Subsidiarity-based economic model</span><span class="token token bold" style="color: rgb(43, 48, 59);">**</span><span> — dignified stipend 
</span></span><span>   plus contribution bonuses, not charity and not employment
</span><span>
</span><span>We propose three-year pilot, initial funding €3-8M, launching 
</span><span>in German legal/social domain (which is unusually well-suited 
</span><span>due to existing technical infrastructure and author's direct 
</span><span>engagement with target populations), expanding to additional 
</span><span>domains and geographies based on empirical outcomes.
</span><span>
</span><span>This document is offered to potential foundation partners, 
</span><span>academic collaborators, corporate sponsors, and policy 
</span><span>stakeholders as basis for dialogue and refinement.
